The Chain Reaction Algorithm is an important part of any match-3 game as it creates a dynamic and engaging gameplay experience. In order to implement this algorithm in Unity C#, follow these steps:

1. Start by creating a method that checks for matches in the game board. This can be done by iterating over all the game pieces in the board and checking if they have any neighboring pieces that match their type. If a match is found, add it to a list of matches.

2. Once you have a list of matches, sort them by the number of pieces they contain. Starting with the match with the fewest pieces, remove all the game pieces in that match from the board.

3. After removing the pieces from the board, check if any of the remaining pieces in the board were moved as a result of the removal. If so, repeat step 1 to check for any new matches that were created by the shifting of pieces.

4. If no new matches were created, move on to the match with the next highest number of pieces and repeat step 2.

5. Continue this process until all matches have been resolved and no new matches are created. This ensures that all possible chain reactions are triggered and the player is rewarded with higher scores and power-ups.

Here is some sample code to get you started:

```
private List<List<GamePiece>> matches = new List<List<GamePiece>>();

private void CheckMatches() 
{
    foreach (var piece in board.pieces) 
    {
        List<GamePiece> match = GetMatch(piece);
        if (match != null) 
        {
            matches.Add(match);
        }
    }
}

private List<GamePiece> GetMatch(GamePiece piece) 
{
    List<GamePiece> match = new List<GamePiece>();
    if (piece == null) 
    {
        return null;
    }
    foreach (var neighbor in piece.GetNeighbors()) 
    {
        if (neighbor != null && neighbor.type == piece.type) 
        {
            match.Add(neighbor);
        }
    }
    if (match.Count >= 2) 
    {
        match.Add(piece);
        return match;
    }
    return null;
}

private void ResolveMatches() 
{
    matches.Sort((x, y) => x.Count.CompareTo(y.Count));
    foreach (var match in matches) 
    {
        board.RemovePieces(match);
        board.ShiftPieces();
    }
    matches.Clear();
}
```

This code checks for matches in the board, sorts them by their size, and removes them from the board, triggering a shift of pieces. It then repeats the process until all matches have been resolved. You can add additional functionality to the algorithm, such as adding power-ups or special effects, to make your game even more engaging.

To create a Chain Reaction Algorithm for a Match-3 game in Unity C# involves the following steps:

1. Create a new C# script named "ChainReactionManager".
2. Define a new public delegate named "OnActionIsRequired", and create an event with this delegate.
3. Create a reference to your board or grid script that manages the tiles.
4. Create a helper function `CheckAndCollapseColumns` to handle checking and collapsing for each column separately.
5. Create a helper function `CollapseColumn` to collapse a column when a match is made.
6. Create a function named "ResetAndRefillGrid" to fill up empty grid spaces with new tiles.
7. Execute the chain reaction algorithm by detecting and handling matches, collapsing columns, and refilling the grid.

Here's a basic implementation of the algorithm:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class ChainReactionManager : MonoBehaviour
{
    public delegate void OnActionIsRequired();
    public static event OnActionIsRequired OnCollapseComplete;

    public Board board; // Reference to the Board script.

    private void Start()
    {
        // Subscribe to the OnMatchComplete event to trigger the chain reaction.
        MatchManager.OnMatchComplete += CheckAndCollapseColumns;
    }

    private void OnDestroy()
    {
        MatchManager.OnMatchComplete -= CheckAndCollapseColumns;
    }

    private void CheckAndCollapseColumns()
    {
        bool actionRequired = false;

        // Iterate through the columns.
        for (int col = 0; col < board.width; col++)
        {
            if (CollapseColumn(col))
            {
                actionRequired = true;
            }
        }

        if (actionRequired)
        {
            StartCoroutine(ResetAndRefillGrid());
        }
        else
        {
            OnCollapseComplete?.Invoke();
        }
    }

    private bool CollapseColumn(int column)
    {
        bool collapseExecuted = false;
        List<Tile> emptyTiles = new List<Tile>();

        // Loop through the tiles in the selected column.
        for (int row = 0; row < board.height; row++)
        {
            if (board.tiles[column, row].IsEmpty())
            {
                emptyTiles.Add(board.tiles[column, row]);
            }
            else if (emptyTiles.Count > 0)
            {
                board.SwapTiles(board.tiles[column, row], emptyTiles[0]);
                emptyTiles.RemoveAt(0);
                emptyTiles.Add(board.tiles[column, row]);
                collapseExecuted = true;
            }
        }

        return collapseExecuted;
    }

    private IEnumerator ResetAndRefillGrid()
    {
        // Wait for collapse animation to be completed.
        yield return new WaitForSeconds(board.swapAnimationTime);

        // Reset and refill the grid.
        board.ResetGrid();
        yield return new WaitForSeconds(board.fillAnimationTime);

        // Rerun the match detection and chain reaction if new matches are found.
        if (MatchManager.Instance.DetectMatches())
        {
            MatchManager.Instance.HandleMatches();
        }
        else
        {
            OnCollapseComplete?.Invoke();
        }
    }
}
```

With this implementation, your Match-3 game should now have a chain reaction triggered whenever matches are made. Create the script, attach it to a GameObject, and ensure it has a reference to the Board script. Additionally, make sure your Tile and MatchManager scripts support the needed functionality.

